Mexican Stocks: America Movil, Grupo Mexico, Maxcom Shares Drop

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   J .   L e v i n
-- 
2011-04-18T16:59:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/mexican-stocks-america-movil-grupo-mexico-maxcom-shares-drop.html
The following companies are having
unusual price changes in  Mexico  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 12:07 p.m. New York time.  The IPC index fell 1.5 percent to 36,416.44, as it headed
for the biggest decline in a month. Standard & Poor’s put a
“negative” outlook on the AAA credit rating of the U.S.,
citing a “material risk” the nation’s leaders will fail to
deal with rising budget deficits and debt. Mexico sends about 80
percent of its exports to the U.S.  America Movil  SAB (AMXL MM) retreated 1.8 percent to 33.38
pesos. The wireless carrier controlled by billionaire  Carlos Slim  said Mexico’s antitrust agency levied a fine of 12 billion
pesos ($1.02 billion) against its Mexico unit for
anticompetitive practices, according to an April 15 statement.  Grupo Mexico SAB (GMEXICOB MM), the country’s largest
mining company, plunged 3.2 percent to 38.65 pesos. Copper for
July delivery dropped 7.5 cents, or 1.7 percent, to $4.2030 a
pound on the Comex in  New York .  Maxcom Telecomunicaciones SAB (MAXCOMCP MM) declined 2.8
percent to 5.29 pesos. The telecommunications company said
Jacques Gliksberg will replace Eduardo Vazquez as chairman of
its board of directors. Vazquez will remain on the board,
according to a statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan J. Levin in Mexico City at 
 jlevin20@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
